    {
      "id": "e6b4d4b4_857f58e0",
      "file_path": "testsuites/performance/src/main/resources/testplans/clearuppolicies.sh",
      "patchset_number": 1,
      "line": 39,
      "message": "oh, I see - it's splitting it into separate arguments when passing to send_delete_request().  One way around that, assuming this is executed with \"bash\" instead of \"sh\" would be to add this after line 30 and then use $ARG instead of $1:\n\n  ARG=\"${@}\"          # combine all function arguments into one\n  ARG=${ARG// /}      # strip out intervening whitespace\n\nIf this is to be executed with \"sh\", then could use \"sed\" to strip the whitespace instead.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 811,
        "name": "Jim Hahn",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "jrh3@att.com",
        "username": "jrh3"
      },
      "updated": "2020-05-19 12:56:12.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "604f059b_a97b4fbd",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "78a5f6a6_8b9eb939",
      "file_path": "testsuites/performance/src/main/resources/testplans/clearuppolicies.sh",
      "patchset_number": 1,
      "line": 39,
      "message": "I wonder would it be better to keep it as it is so that it can be used by both bash and sh, or would you prefer to pick one and stick with it? In my testing I use sh locally but bash on the vm",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 6593,
        "name": "Ross Carter",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "ross.carter@est.tech",
        "username": "RossC"
      },
      "updated": "2020-05-19 13:33:07.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "e6b4d4b4_857f58e0",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "3b936bc3_4ee9f62d",
      "file_path": "testsuites/performance/src/main/resources/testplans/clearuppolicies.sh",
      "patchset_number": 1,
      "line": 39,
      "message": "\"sed\" will work with either.  Can use this instead of the other lines:\n\n  ARG=$(echo $@ | sed 's/ //g')",
      "author": {
